@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Just  double-click  the  `InstallSignArch'  icon,  and  follow the
prompts.
    If  you  don't have or like the C= `Installer' utility, it's still
simple.   Just  copy  `SignArch.rexx' to your REXX:  assign/directory,
and  `SignArch'  to  c:   or somewhere else in your path.  Please mind
that  both  files have the `s'-flag set, use the Protect command to do
this.  In addition, you'll have to copy the `ChkASCII' to somewhere in
your  path,  and  make sure  that  as well `@{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}' as `MD5SUM' also are
there.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "UsageShell" "Usage of shell commands"
@TOC "MAIN"
                               -=+<>+=-
@{b}                        Rexx script invocators@{ub}
                   (these will archive, sign, etc.)
                               -=+<>+=-

@{b}NAME@{ub}
    SignArch -- signs & archives according to commandfile given

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
    This  will startup the main REXX script, and parse the @{"commandfile" LINK "CommandFile"}
    given,  performing the necessary signing, archiving and (eventual)
    encryption.

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
    SignArch COMMANDFILE

    @{"COMMANDFILE" LINK "CommandFile"}
        The filename of a commandfile created using the Graphical User
        Interface  (GUI),  or  handcrafted  using the guidelines found
        @{"here" LINK "CommandFileCreate"}.

    If  no  @{"COMMANDFILE" LINK "CommandFile"}  is  specified,  it  will be requested using a
    file-requester,      if      both      `reqtools.library'      and
    `rexxreqtools.library'  is installed.  If not, a shell prompt will
    be issued.

@{b}RESULT@{ub}
    A  @{"sumfile" LINK "SUMFILE"} and an archive will be created, according to the user's
    desires & wishes.

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
    This  is  exactly the same as selecting the @{"Create archive" LINK "ProjExec"} item in
    the @{"Project" LINK "Menuoverview" 3} menu, found in @{"SignArchGUI" LINK "UsageGUI"}.

    Much of the same effect may be obtained by using @{"ShA" LINK "UsageShell" 48}.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
    No  more than those found in the main REXX script, in other words:
    None known :)

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
    @{"ShA" LINK "UsageShell" 48},   @{"Usage   of   Graphical  User  Interface" LINK "UsageGUI"},  @{"Commandfiles" LINK "Commandfile"} and
    @{"the creation of them" LINK "CommandfileCreate"}.


                               -=+<>+=-

@{b}NAME@{ub}
    ShA -- LhA 'substitute', signs & archives according to template

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
    Will  process  the  commandline  given,  and create a CommandFile,
    which  will  passed  to  SignArch.   May be considered as LhA with
    message digesting possibilities.

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
    ARCHIVE,SUMFILE/A,ADDARMOR/S,ADDCOMM/K,ARCLIVE/S,AUTOCHK/S,
    BANNERS/K,DEEPCHK/S,ENCRYPT/K,ENDWAIT/S,INCTEXT/K,NOKEYADD/S,
    ROOTDIR/K,SIGNAME/K,SUMICON/S,WAITCOM/K,FILES/A/M

    Although the template may seem enormous, only three parameters are
    needed:

    @{"ARCHIVE" LINK "ARCHIVE"}
        Name of the archive to put files within. Must be specified, unless
        @{"SUMONLY" LINK "SUMONLY"} is specified.

    @{"SUMFILE/A" LINK "SUMFILE"}
        Name of the file to put message digests within

    FILES/A/M
        Files to sign/archive.  Multiple files are of course allowed.

    You  may  also  specify the following keywords/switches, which are
    equivalents to CommandFile options:

    @{"ADDARMOR/S" LINK "ADDARMOR"}
        Make  the  archive output as 7-bit ASCII, suitable for e-mail.
        (Boolean)

    @{"ADDCOMM/K" LINK "ADDCOMM"}
        Add  a  user-specified  command  to  the  @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}, making it a
        script

    @{"ARCLIVE/S" LINK "ARCLIVE"}
        Don't  delete the uncrypted archive when @{"ENCRYPT" LINK "ENCRYPT"} is specified.
        (Boolean)

    @{"AUTOCHK/S" LINK "AUTOCHK"}
        Add commands to the sumfile, making it self-checking (Boolean)

    @{"BANNERS/K" LINK "BANNERS"}
        Add a user-specified line of info, copyright, etc.

    @{"DEEPCHK/S" LINK "DEEPCHK"}
        Check whole file when determining whether it is text (Boolean)

    @{"ENCRYPT/K" LINK "ENCRYPT"}
        Encrypt the archive to the person specified

    @{"ENDWAIT/S" LINK "ENDWAIT"}
        Only  issue  the  @{"WAITCOM" LINK "WAITCOM"}  command  at the end of the checking
        script (Boolean)

    @{"INCTEXT/K" LINK "INCTEXT"}
        Include the user-specified textfile in the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}

    @{"NOKEYADD/S" LINK "NOKEYADD"}
        Don't  include  the  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}  public  key  used for signing in the
        @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"} (Boolean)

    @{"ROOTDIR/K" LINK "ROOTDIR"}
        The specified directory will be used as current directory when
        archiving

    @{"SIGNAME/K" LINK "SIGNAME"}
        The name of the @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} key to use when signing

    @{"SUMICON/S" LINK "SUMICON"}
        Message digest .info files also (Boolean)
       
    @{"SUMONLY/S" LINK "SUMONLY"}
        Only  create  the  sumfile,  don't  create  any  archive.  The
        ARCHIVE should be omitted if this is specified.

    @{"WAITCOM/K" LINK "WAITCOM"}
        Command  issued  between  the  cryptographic commands when the
        user  executes  the  @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}  -  only relevant when @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} is
        specified.

    Currently, the current directory when running ShA must be the same
    as the files to be archived are located within.


@{b}NOTES@{ub}
    Needs Kick 2.0 or higher.

    "/K"  after  a  parameter  in  the  template,  means  that it is a
    keyword,  "/S"  that  it  is  a  switch (boolean), "/A" that it is
    required and "/M" that multiple files may be specified as args.

    Pure, may be made resident.


@{b}RESULT@{ub}
    The  files  will  be  archived,  message  digested, signed and, if
    selected, the final archive will be encrypted.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
    You  may  currently  only specify one encryption recipient and one
    banner   via   this   interface  (the  SignArch  program  supports
    unlimited).

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
    Documentation for AmigaDOS templates

                               -=+<>+=-
@{b}NAME@{ub}
    AddSum -- add a signature file to an existing archive

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
    This  one  will  unarchive an existing archive, message digest the
    files  and  sign them, and add this file to the archive.  The name
    of the sumfile will be set to the base of the archive's name, e.g.
    'ram:foobar.lha' will get a sumfile of 'foobar.sum'.

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
    ARCHIVE,TEMPDIR

    ARCHIVE
        Archive   that   is   to   be   message  digested,  each  file
        individually.   If  no  archive is specified, a file-requester
        will  pop  up,  if  you  use  the  shell version to invoke the
        script, and have installed RequestFile.

    TMPDIR
        By  default,  the  archive  will  be unarchived to T:.  If the
        archive is big, you may wish to unarchive them somewhere else.
        This may be specified here.

@{b}RESULT@{ub}
    A sumfile will be created and added.

@{b}NOTES@{ub}

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
    You are currently set with a preset options.

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}


                               -=+<>+=-
@{b}                            Other programs@{ub}
      (used by the script, may be nice for other purposes also)
                               -=+<>+=-


@{b}NAME@{ub}
    ChkASCII -- Checks whether a file is text or binary


@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
    FILENAME/A,WHOLEFILE/S,VERBOSE/S

    FILENAME/A
        Name of the file to determine whether is text or binary.

    WHOLEFILE/S
        Normally,  if  the  first  1k  can  be classified as text, the
        entire  file will be assumed to be text.  Specifying this will
        force  that  the  whole  file  to  be  checked  before  it  is
        considered as text.

    VERBOSE/S
        Normally,  processing  is 100% quiet.  This gives you progress
        info, and results.

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
    Needs Kick 2.0 or higher.

    Pure, may be made resident.

    The  check  is  performed,  by  looking  for non-ASCII characters.
    Aborts at the first binary character found, most binary files will
    therefore be processed very quick.

    Allowed 'text' bytes are the one defined in ANSI X3.64-1979, that
    is:

    Graphic group 0:    ' ' to '~' plus DEL             ( 32 to 127)
    Graphic group 1:    ' ' (Non-breaking space) to '˙' (160 to 255)
    Control group 0:     TAB, NL, FF, CR, ESC
                         0x9,0xa,0xc,0xd,0x1b
    Control group 1:      SS2, SS3, DCS, CSI,  ST, OSC,  PM, APC
                         0x8E,0x8F,0x90,0x9B,0x9C,0x9D,0x9E,0x9F

    Is used by the REXX script.

@{b}RESULT@{ub}
    OK      = file is ASCII
    WARN    = file is binary
    FAIL    = Unable to check

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
    Rather weak check.

                               -=+<>+=-

@{b}NAME@{ub}
    ChkDate -- checks that the date is set correct

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
    Works with all Kickstarts.

    Pure, may be made resident (for whatever purpose that has).

    Is used by the REXX script.

@{b}RESULTS@{ub}
    Returns WARN if system time is before 15.  November 1994, OK if it
    is  after.   Thus, we can warn in most cases when the user doesn't
    have  a  realtime  clock,  and  has  forgotten  to  set  the  date
    correctly.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
    The user should be able to push the 'checkdate' forward.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Commandfile" "The commandfile"
@TOC "MAIN"
    The  command  file  is  the  file which partly control the script,
partly  give  it the information it needs, such as filenames, names of
@{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} keys, etc.

    By  @{"using the  GUI" LINK "UsageGUI"},  you will avoid the details of such files, it
will take care of everything.

    And  example  of  a  hand-crafted  commandfile,  can  be  found in
`SA.fls', which was included with this distribution.

    If you wish to know the exact specification for this command file,
click @{"here" LINK "CommandfileCreate"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CommandfileCreate" "Creating the commandfile"
@TOC "MAIN"
         Here's  how to create the commandfile, step by step.

NOTE:   You  DON'T  have  to  read/understand this in order to use the
Graphical  User Interface!  This information is provided for those who
wish   to   write   their   own   utils  utilizing  the  REXX  script.
'AddSum.rexx' is an example of such.

First  of all, please note that lines beginning with `;', are ignored,
if  you wish to comment your work.  For an example, look at the SA.fls
file, the file used to create this distribution.

    1. The  first line of the file MUST read `!!FILELIST!!' (excluding
       the quotes, of course).

    2. The  next  lines have to begin with `***', thus specifying them
       as  options, with a possible parameter.  Please do not use more
       than  one space between option and parameter.  There is no need
       to  enclose  the  parameter  with  double  quotes, that is `"',
       unless  the  parameter contains leading or trailing blanks.  If
       not,  the rest of the line will be taken as parameter.  Neither
       the option nor an eventual parameter is case-sensitive.

       The  following  options  are  valid:

       @{u}@{b}Name@{uu}@{ub}     @{u}@{b}Required@{uu}@{ub} | @{u}@{b}Needs parameters@{uu}@{ub}

       @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}  Yes      | Yes
       @{"ARCHIVE" LINK "SIGNAME"}  Yes      | Yes

       @{"ADDARMOR" LINK "ADDARMOR"} No       | No
       @{"ADDCOMM" LINK "ADDCOMM"}  No       | Yes
       @{"ARCLIVE" LINK "ARCLIVE"}  No       | No
       @{"ASCCHAR" LINK "ASCCHAR"}  No       | Yes
       @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"}  No       | No
       @{"BANNERS" LINK "BANNERS"}  No       | Optional
       @{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"}  No       | Yes
       @{"DEEPCHK" LINK "DEEPCHK"}  No       | No
       @{"ENCRYPT" LINK "ENCRYPT"}  No       | Yes
       @{"ENDWAIT" LINK "ENDWAIT"}  No       | No
       @{"EXECCMD" LINK "EXECCMD"}  No       | Yes
       @{"INCTEXT" LINK "INCTEXT"}  No       | Yes
       @{"LASTOPT" LINK "LASTOPT"}  No       | No
       @{"NOKEYADD" LINK "NOKEYADD"} No       | No
       @{"NOWILDS" LINK "NOWILDS"}  No       | No
       @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"}  No       | Yes
       @{"SIGNAME" LINK "SIGNAME"}  No       | Yes
       @{"SUMICON" LINK "SUMICON"}  No       | No
       @{"SUMONLY" LINK "SUMONLY"}  No       | No
       @{"WAITCOM" LINK "WAITCOM"}  No       | Optional
       @{"WAITRET" LINK "WAITRET"}  No       | No

    3. Now  the  list  of  files  should  follow,  all relative to the
       @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"}  parameter.  Blank  lines  are ignored.  Remember that
       disk information should NOT be present, e.g.  skip volume names
       like  `dh0:'.   Also,  leading  and  trailing blanks and double
       quotes (`"') will be stripped off.  Of course, use wildcards as
       much  as possible - you won't have to type that much then.  The
       sumfile  should  NOT be included in this list, it will be added
       automagically.

       When  you  are  about  to create the commandfile (by hand, that
       is),  things get simpler if you type the following commandline,
       being in the rootdir of your distribution:

       List >RAM:Fls LFORMAT "%f%s" ALL FILES

       The  file  RAM:Fls  will now contain a list over all the files,
       which you can edit.



    4. That's  all!   In a nutshell:
        First line: !!FILELIST!!

        The next line should contain:
            @{"***ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"} <dir-used-as-current-dir-while-archiving>

        Next lines MUST contain:
            @{"***ARCHIVE" LINK "ARCHIVE"} <name-of-archive>
            @{"***SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"} <name-of-sumfile-relative-to-rootdir>

        If you wish to add more options, do it here.

        The   remaining  lines  should  contain  a  list  of  files  &
        wildcards, separated by a linefeed.

       If  you  still are confused, please take a look at the included
       `SA.fls' file, which is an example of practical use.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SUMFILE" "SUMFILE"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} SUMFILE
@{b}Required        :@{ub} Yes
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

The  following  parameter  specifies  the  name  of the file where the
message  digests  and  sums will  be  placed, relative to the @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"}
parameter.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ARCHIVE" "ARCHIVE"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ARCHIVE
@{b}Required        :@{ub} Yes
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This  is  the  name  of  the LhA archive the files will be put within,
relative to @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"}, as all filenames are.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ADDARMOR" "ADDARMOR"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ADDARMOR
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This  command  will make sure that the final archive output ends up as
7-bit  ASCII, suitable for posting via e-mail.  Currently, only @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} is
supported   as  encoder  (yes,  you  may  ASCII-fy  with  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}  without
necessarily encrypting), UU-encoding is currently not supported.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ADDCOMM" "ADDCOMM"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ADDCOMM
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

The  parameter  will  be  added  to  the front of the signature of the
script,  enabling  specifying a kind of script.  If the @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} option
is  specified,  the  command  will  be issued before the cryptographic
part.   If you do not specify the @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} option, please let the final
ADDCOMM  parameter  be  `Quit'.   More  than one ADDCOMM option may be
specified, and will be added in the same order as they were specified.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ARCLIVE" "ARCLIVE"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ARCLIVE
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

If  you  specify  the  @{"ENCRYPT" LINK "ENCRYPT"}  option, the noncrypted archive will by
default  be  deleted/wiped.  Specifying ARCLIVE will leave the archive
on disk.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ASCCHAR" "ASCCHAR"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ASCCHAR
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Exactly the same as @{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"}, although an ASCII message digesting is
forced. Please read the description of @{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AUTOCHK" "AUTOCHK"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} AUTOCHK
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

By  default, only  the signatures are put in the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"} file, plus a
quick  description  of  how to check the files.  In some cases you may
wish  to  make  this  process  automatic.   To  make  the  script work
properly,  a  `-----BEGIN'  executable  is included automagically with
your  distribution  (which  btw.   is  included  with this one).

@{b}NOTE:   THIS  IS  A  SECURITY  HOLE.   THE  '-----BEGIN'  FILE  MAY BE
INFECTED,  OR REPLACED.  COMMANDS INFECTING THE SYSTEM MAY BE ADDED IN
FRONT  OF  THE PGP SIGNED PART.  IT IS INDEED DISCOURAGED THAT YOU USE
THIS OPTION.@{ub}

To  make  sure  you  are aware of this problem, you will be asked each
time  for  confirmation.   To  avoid  this,  add  this  line  to  your
S:User-Startup file:

    SetEnv "SignArchOpts" "do_not_ask_for_confirmation_of_autochk"

The -----BEGIN file is added because doing so will:
    1) avoid  AmigaDOS  message  like 'Can't find command '-----BEGIN'
(the ENTIRE file is interpreted as a normal AmigaDOS script!)
    2) check       that       the       @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}       begins      with
'-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----'   and  TWO  linefeeds.   This  is
necessary  to  avoid a bug in @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.  Both the script and the executable
should work with all kickstarts.

As  the  file  has  to  be  recreated for each run and is differs from
archive to archive, the only equality is that there is one code chunk
of 300 bytes, and then a data chunk which is more or less the length
of the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}'s name.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "BANNERS" "BANNERS"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} BANNERS
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Opt
@{b}Description:@{ub}

The  parameter will, if the @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} is not specified, just be added at
the  top  of  the  @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}  file  (of  course  behind eventual @{"ADDCOMM" LINK "ADDCOMM"}
commands).   If  @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"}  is  specified, the parameter will be Echo'ed
upon  execution of the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"} file.  More than one BANNERS option may
be  specified,  and  will  be  added  in  the  same order as they were
specified.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "BINCHAR" "BINCHAR"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} BINCHAR
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Usually, the detection between an ASCII text and a binary file is done
automagically.  In some cases, however, it might be useful to override
this  setting  on a particular file.  If you put the character you use
as  parameter here, in front of a file, it will be message digested in
binary  mode.   If the filename contains wildcards, ALL files matching
that pattern will be forced to binary.

Some characters are not allowed used:  `;', `/', `:', `*', `"' and ` '
(blank space).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "DEEPCHK" "DEEPCHK"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} DEEPCHK
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Specifying this flag makes the ASCII check run through the entire file
(still  aborting  at  first  `binary' value), to determine whether the
file  is  ASCII  or  not.   In  some cases this may be preferable, the
default is to only check the first kilobyte.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ENCRYPT" "ENCRYPT"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ENCRYPT
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

In  some cases, you may wish to encrypt the final archive.  Specifying
this  option  will  do  so,  and  the  parameter  is  the  name of the
recipient.  If you wish to encrypt the archive to multiple recipients,
specify multiple ENCRYPT options, one for each name.

Please  note  that  the  extension of the archive will be changed from
".lha" to ".lzh", to fit with the internal recognition in @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} of LhArc
archives.   The  noncrypted archive will be wiped off the disk, unless
you decide to let the archive live by specifying the @{"ARCLIVE" LINK "ARCLIVE"} option.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ENDWAIT" "ENDWAIT"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ENDWAIT
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This  option  has  only  effect  if  you  specify it together with the
@{"WAITCOM" LINK "WAITCOM"} and @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK" option.  Entering this option, you select that the
wait  command  will  ONLY  be  executed  at the end of the script, not
between each check, as default.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "EXECCMD" "EXECCMD"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} EXECCMD
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Will  execute  the  parameter  as a shell command.  Might be useful in
some  cases,  if  you consider the commandfile as a `makefile' for the
archive.  Please read the notes for @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"} option.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "INCTEXT" "INCTEXT"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} INCTEXT
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Will  include  a text file with the sumfile, making the sumfile also a
kind  of readme file or whatever.  The text will be put after eventual
commands  added  by @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} or/and @{"ADDCOMM" LINK "ADDCOMM"}.  The parameter is the name
of  the  text  file,  and  must  be relative to the @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"} parameter.
Currently,  multiple INCTEXT's are not allowed.  Please read the notes
for @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"} opt.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "LASTOPT" "LASTOPT"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} LASTOPT
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This option simply tells the script that this was the last option, and
that the list of files begin now. Not really needed, but just in case
all your files begin with '***'...:)
Warning: This MUST, naturally, be the very last *** option!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOKEYADD" "NOKEYADD"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} NOKEYADD
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Specifying  this  option will DISABLE the automatic adding of your @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}
public  key  required  to  check  the signature.  May be useful if the
archive  only  will be distributed to people that already possess your
key.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOWILDS" "NOWILDS"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} NOWILDS
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This  option  will turn off wildcard matching and file name expansion.
Mind  the  latter,  you  MUST give the filenames in the same format as
'List LFORMAT %f%s'  would  give  them!   If  not,  strange things may
happen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ROOTDIR" "ROOTDIR"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} ROOTDIR
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

The  parameter  will  be  used  as current directory when creating the
archive.   If  not  specified, the current directory when starting the
script  will  be  used instead.  You should put this as the very first
line in your commandfile, to avoid trouble with for instance  @{"EXECCMD" LINK "EXECCMD"}
& @{"INCTEXT" LINK "INCTEXT"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SIGNAME" "SIGNAME"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} SIGNAME
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Yes
@{b}Description:@{ub}

The parameter will be used as your name when talking to @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}, and this
name will be used to find the key to sign everything with.  It's up to
you whether you choose the hex value or a part of your real name.

Please  note  if  you  don't specify this option, the MyName parameter
found in pgp.config in your PGPPATH dir (if properly initialized, that
is) will  be used as your name when talking to @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.  If this can't be
found, the first key on your secret keyring will be used.

If this information is not available, or initialized, the first key on
your  secret keyring will be used for signing, and its matching key on
the pubring will be extracted.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SUMICON" "SUMICON"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} SUMICON
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

By  default,  icon  files  are not summed, because just changing their
position  on  the  WB  is  enough to make the check fail.  To override
this,  specify this option.  If you wish to only override this setting
on one file, specify the @{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"} option, and prepend the filename with
the @{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"} character.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SUMONLY" "SUMONLY"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} SUMONLY
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

Specifying  this  option  will just create the @{"Sumfile" LINK "SUMFILE"}, and not do any
archiving, encryption, etc.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WAITCOM" "WAITCOM"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} WAITCOM
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} Opt
@{b}Description:@{ub}

When  @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"}  is  enabled,  you may wish to execute a command between
each  of the cryptographic commands, so that the user can evaluate the
output.   However,  this is making the security hole even bigger.  For
instance,  if  you  include the wait command with your distribution, a
command  will  be  run  BEFORE  it has been checked with MD5SUM.  This
command may have been rewritten by someone, to patch @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} and MD5SUM to
not work correctly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WAITRET" "WAITRET"
@TOC "CommandfileCreate"
@{b}Name            :@{ub} WAITRET
@{b}Required        :@{ub} No
@{b}Needs parameters:@{ub} No
@{b}Description:@{ub}

This option will, if anything goes wrong, or the script is breaked,
ask the user to press return. Useful the console will be closed
immediately when the script finished, as the user may get a chance to
see what actually went wrong.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOTES" "Notes"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}When can you trust such a file of message digests? (READ THIS)@{ub}

    Such  a  file  of  message digests can ONLY be trusted, if the @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}
public  key  can  be  verified.   The  entire  security of the package
depends  on  that  the  receiver  can  get  your  key  confirmed, e.g.
verified  that  it really  is  yours.   @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}  keys  with  only  a  few
signatures, are difficult to verify the ownership of, because it isn't
probable  that the receiver has the keys of the people who signed your
key  and  trusts them.  @{b}@{i}A PGP key without signatures is worth close to
nothing.@{ui}@{ub}

    Therefore,  you  should  try  to  collect  as  many  signatures as
possible.   Also,  you  should include a notice in your documentation,
saying that the message digests only can be trusted if your public key
can be verified.


@{b}But, what exactly is a message digest?@{ub}

    Message digests are more or less similar to checksums, except that
they @{i}can't be reverse engineered.@{ui}  As the designer says:

     "It is conjectured that the difficulty of coming up with two
     messages having the same message digest is on the order of 2^64
     operations, and that the difficulty of coming up with any message
     having a given message digest is on the order of 2^128 operations.
     The MD5 algorithm has been carefully scrutinized for weaknesses.
     It is, however, a relatively new algorithm and further security
     analysis is of course justified, as is the case with any new
     proposal of this sort. The level of security provided by MD5
     should be sufficient for implementing very high security hybrid
     digital signature schemes based on MD5 and the RSA public-key
     cryptosystem."

    As  you  may understand, there's no other way known than the brute
force  attack to create a file with a given message digest (checksum).
Thus,  if  one  can  with  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}  verify  that  the  message digests are
unmodified,  and  the  MD5SUM doesn't report any errors when checking,
one  can trust that the files have passed untouched.  Another word for
message digests is signatures.


@{b}I  can't  get  my  PGP  keys displayed, the program refuses to archive
everything and so on...what can I do?@{ub}

If  this  only  happens  once in a while, the problem is probably only
that  not  enough  memory  is  available to start @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} to get the keys.
Remember,  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} is a big program, and needs about 150kb  free memory to
start.

However, if the program never shows any keys on your keyring (assuming
that  there are some there :), something is probably configured wrong.
Check that the following is correctly initialized:

1. PGPPATH (look in the @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} documentation)
2. @{"Global settings" LINK "ProjGlobSett"}


@{b}I'm  fed  up  with  the requester when I use the AUTOCHK option!  I @{i}AM@{ui}
aware of the dangers, and do NOT wish to be disturbed.  What do I do?@{ub}

Read one of these sections:  @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} or @{"Add script commands" LINK "AddScriptGUI"}, and add
the line specified to your S:User-Startup.


@{b}What exactly does the '-----BEGIN' file?@{ub}

    To  make  the  autochecking  script  work properly, a `-----BEGIN'
executable  is  included  automagically  with your distribution (which
btw.  is included with this one).

This  file  will:
    1) avoid  AmigaDOS  message  like 'Can't find command '-----BEGIN'
(the ENTIRE file is interpreted as a normal AmigaDOS script!)
    2) check       that       the       @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}       begins      with
'-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----'   and  TWO  linefeeds.   This  is
necessary  to  avoid a bug in @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.  Both the script and the executable
should work with all kickstarts.

    However,  many programs do not like that program names starts with
one  or  multiple  "-"'s  (for  instance, MD5SUM, LhA).  I've tried do
create  workarounds  for  these, but future releases of MD5SUM and LhA
may  have  corrected  these problems, so the workarounds may then just
cause trouble...:)
    The  workarounds work OK with the Sept 1993 version of MD5SUM, and
v1.50 of LhA.


@{b}Can I use previously created files with all the filenames to archive?@{ub}

    Yes, you can, as long as each filename is separated with a return.
In  the  GUI, if you already have a list of filenames separated with a
<return>,  use  Settings->Files->Load...   to  load the files into the
display.   Just  ignore the warning that shows up, click that you wish
to continue.

    If  you still prefer to create the file by hand, you may of course
simply include the file at the end of the file.


@{b}Why ARexx, instead of some (quicker) compilable language, like C?@{ub}

    First  of  all  because  it  is  simple, and needs no compilation.
Thus,  it  is  easy for even a novice to examine that the program does
not  contain  any  trap  doors,  something  which  may occur also if a
C-source  is  included,  as  most  people  don't  mind recompiling the
programs they get.
    Secondly, because it is an easy language to develop within, and is
indeed  supported  by C=, being the only @{i}programming@{ui} language directly
runnable uncompiled from Shell, with no command in front.

    Of course, the GUI is written in C...:)


@{b}The REXX script is far to slow! Can something be done?@{ub}

    It  might  be  a good idea to run a Rexx optimizer/compiler on the
script  - especially the option parsing will be speeded up then.  This
was not done with the distributed script to maintain readability.

    A  REXX  optimizer  I  recommend,  is RexxOpt by Proxity Softworks
(Ulrich Sibiller/sibilluh@trick.informatik.uni-stuttgart.de), found in
the  archive REXXOPT_1.5.LHA somewhere on AmiNet.  This will strip all
unneeded comments, blanks, blank lines - thus making the program about
20% shorter.  This will make the Rexx parser run faster.

@{b}Why isn't the source for the executables included?@{ub}

    As  you  may  have  noticed,  the source for the GUI and the shell
commands  are  not  included.   It  is  not  because  I  wish  to hide
something,  but  rather  because  it's  big  (The  GUI  itself  is 120
kilobytes!  - LOTS of tabs, though...), and, for most people, not very
interesting.   Thus,  most  people  are  more likely to appreciate the
reduced size of the archive, than the possibility to study the source.

    The  only  source  included, is the one for the '-----BEGIN' file,
because  it is important that people trust and understand the function
this file.

    However,  if  you  wish  to  have  the  source for the GUI and the
remaining  executables  I've  made,  just  send a letter to one of the
@{"addresses" LINK "Address"} you may contact me at, and I'll happily return it.

MIND YOU:  If you wish to receive the source via snail-mail, make sure
           to include:
                1) A disk
                2) A self-addressed envelope
                3) $2 USD if you live within Europe, $3 if you live
                   outside, to cover postage.

           I will also NOT upload it to boards outside Oslo.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs" "Bugs"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Haven't  found  any...hopefully  I've cleaned it up...:) There has
been  some problems with crashes upon startup, but this has apparently
been caused by other programs.

    There  is  a  bug in most versions of @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}, making its clearsigning
not  secure  at  all,  as  one  may  add  lines at the top without @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}
noticing  it.   The AmigaDOS script avoids this problem partly, by not
using  the  file  itself,  but  the  output @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} produces as source for
message  digests.   You  should also encourage the user to use the @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}
output as source when checking the @{"message digests" LINK "Notes" 18}.

    I  also  believe  that  there  also is a bug in amigaguide.library
v39.11,  because when I specify that the link should go to line 158 in
a  node,  it  jumps  to  line 168, and so on.  It seems like this only
occurs  when  the  linenumber  is  above 100.  When this bug is fixed,
strange links may occur.

    Anyway,  if  you  have found an undocumented feature, reproducible
ones  are  preferred.   That  is,  you  ought  to  enclose  a detailed
description  of  what  you  did,  so  the  bug  can be reproduced.  If
possible,  please  include  the files used as arguments when the error
occurred.
@ENDNODE

