@NODE "UsageGUI" "Usage of GUI"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Usage  of  the  Graphical  User  Interface (SignArchGUI) should be
quite  easy,  especially  if you take a look at the explanation of the
commandfile below and is a little familiar with the Amiga.

@{b}STARTUP@{ub}

    To  start the GUI, just double-click its icon.  You may also start
it  by shift-clicking, that is holding <shift> down, click @{i}once@{ui} on the
SignArchGUI  icon, and double-click on a @{"CommandFile" LINK "CommandFile"}.  The commandfile
selected will then automagically be loaded into the GUI. The same will
happen if you simply double-click the @{"CommandFile's" LINK "CommandFile"} icon.

    If  you just wish to create the archive the @{"CommandFile" LINK "CommandFile"} specifies,
you  may  click  once  on  the SignArch (the dummy script's) icon, and
double click on the @{"CommandFile" LINK "CommandFile"}.

    It may also be started from a Shell, template:

SignArchGUI COMMANDFILE

    The commandfile argument is optional, it will be loaded.

@{b}MINIMUM EFFORT@{ub}

    The minimum effort to create an archive, is to:

    1) select  the  files  you  wish  to  archive
    2) select the name of the sumfile (here called Checksumfile)
    3) the name of the archive
    4) select  Project->Create  Archive to create the archive (execute
       the REXX script).

@{b}ONLINE HELP@{ub}

    To get help on an item while the program is running, make sure the
    program  window  is  active,  position  the mouse pointer over the
    gadget  (or hold it over a menuitem), and press the <HELP>-key.  A
    node  in  this  AmigaGuide  will then pop up accordingly, if it is
    installed  in  "HELP:"  or the same directory as the program.  The
    Installer script will take care of this.

@{b}BREAKING AN OPERATION@{ub}

    Some  operations, like adding a zillion files to the the filelist,
    may  take  some  time.   To  interrupt  this,  press CTRL-C in the
    window, or use the Shell "Break" command.

@{b}GADGETS AND MENUS@{ub}

    The user interface can roughly be separated into four parts:

    @{"Files" LINK "FileControl"}       - Where you control file settings
    @{"Encryption" LINK "EncryptControl"}  - Where you set encryption recipients, etc.
    @{"Prefs" LINK "PrefsPart"}       - Where you can set misc. flags
    @{"Menus" LINK "Menuoverview"}       - Loading/saving/etc.

    Needless  to  say,  clicking  the key underlined in a gadget text,
will  change/activate  that gadget.
    NOTE:   If  there  is  a  'fileselect'  gadget to the right of the
gadget,  pressing  <shift>  while  clicking  the key underlined in the
gadget text, will pop up a requester accordingly.
    For  instance,  if  you  hold  <shift>  and press 'r', a directory
requester  pops  up.   If  you  just  push  'r',  the string gadget is
activated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FileControl" "File Control Part"
@TOC "UsageGUI"
The file control part has the following gadgets:

    @{"Root directory" LINK "RootdirGUI"}    - The current directory while archiving
*   @{"Archive" LINK "ArchiveGUI"}           - The file to archive the files within
*   @{"Checksum-file" LINK "SumfileGUI"}     - The file to put the message digests within
    @{"Include textfile" LINK "InctextGUI"}  - Text file to include into the checksum-file
*   @{"Filelist" LINK "FilelistGUI"}          - List of the files to be archived
    @{"Add files" LINK "AddFilesGUI"}         - Add files to the list above
    @{"Rem. files" LINK "RemFilesGUI"}        - Remove files from the list above
    @{"Sort" LINK "SortFilesGUI"}              - Sort the list above

The  items  marked  with  an  asterix  (*),  must  be  initialized  to
something.   If not, the final archiving script won't do anything, and
you will be warned if you try to save the datas to a file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "RootdirGUI" "Root directory"
@TOC "FileControl"
The  contents  of  this  string gadget, will be treated as the @{"ROOTDIR" LINK "ROOTDIR"}
parameter  when  creating the commandfile, and will thus be used as
current directory when archiving begins.

By  clicking  the box to the right of the string gadget, you may use a
directory  requester  to  select  the  root directory, or even easier:
Just let the program try to autofind it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ArchiveGUI" "Archive"
@TOC "FileControl"
The  contents  of  this  string gadget, will be treated as the @{"ARCHIVE" LINK "ARCHIVE"}
parameter  when  creating the commandfile, must be initialized.  Thus,
the  final  archiving  script  won't do anything unless this gadget is
initialized,  and you will be warned if you try to save the datas to a
file.

The filename specified here, is the name of the LhA archive everything
will be put within.

By  clicking  the box to the right of the string gadget, you may use a
file-requester to select the archive.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SumfileGUI" "Checksum-file"
@TOC "FileControl"
The  contents  of  this  string gadget, will be treated as the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}
parameter  when  creating  the commandfile.  Thus, the final archiving
script  won't  do  anything unless this gadget is initialized, and you
will be warned if you try to save the datas to a file.

The  filename  put  here, is the file that the message digests are put
within, and which, finally, is signed with @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.

By  clicking  the box to the right of the string gadget, you may use a
file-requester to select the checksumfile.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "InctextGUI" "Include textfile"
@TOC "FileControl"
The  contents  of  this  string gadget, will be treated as the @{"INCTEXT" LINK "INCTEXT"}
parameter  when  creating the commandfile.  This file will be included
in  the  sumfile,  after  the  script,  if  such  is  specified  (see:
@{"Add script commands" LINK "AddscriptGUI"}).

The  filename  put  here,  should specify the name of a textfile to be
included into the @{"sumfile" LINK "SUMFILE"}.

By  clicking  the box to the right of the string gadget, you may use a
file-requester to select the text to be included.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FilelistGUI" "Filelist"
@TOC "FileControl"
The  listview named FileList contains a list of the files which are to
be  archived.   You  may  use the arrows and scrollbar to the right to
move  up  and down in the list view, select items by clicking on them,
and  use  the  gadgets  below  to  manipulate  it;  namely  @{"Add files" LINK "AddFilesGUI"},
@{"Rem. files" LINK "RemFilesGUI"} and @{"Sort" LINK "SortFilesGUI"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AddFilesGUI" "Add files"
@TOC "FileControl"
By  clicking  this gadget, a file-requester will pop up, where you can
select  the  files which are to be archived.  You may of course select
multiple files.

Sometimes,  after  pressing "Ok" in the file-requester, this requestor
may show up:

                 WARNING: Some files exist above the
                 rootdir. May cause problems when
                 archiving.

This  is  just  a  reminder  that  the  @{"Root  directory" LINK "RootdirGUI"}  gadget is not
correctly initialized, and that you should correct it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "RemFilesGUI" "Rem. Files"
@TOC "FileControl"
By clicking this gadget, the currently selected file (if any), will be
removed from the @{"FileList" LINK "FilelistGUI"} gadget, and will thus NOT be archived.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SortFilesGUI" "Sort (files)"
@TOC "FileControl"
When  you  click this gadget, the contents of the @{"FileList" LINK "FilelistGUI"} gadget will
be sorted alphabetically, making it easier to read.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "EncryptControl" "Encryption Control Part"
@TOC "UsageGUI"
The encryption part has the following parts:

    @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"}     - Encrypt the final archive with @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}?
    @{"Wipe noncrypted" LINK "ArcwipeGUI"}   - Keep the uncrypted version of the archive?
    @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"}    - List of people able to decrypt the archive
    @{"New key" LINK "NewKeyGUI"}           - Add a key to the list above
    @{"Remove" LINK "RemKey"}            - Remove a key from the list above
    @{"Sort" LINK "SortKeyGUI"}              - Sort the list above

These gadgets will be ghosted unless the Encrypt archive prefs item is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "EncryptarchiveGUI" "Encrypt archive"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
Checking  this  box,  indicates  that  you  wish  to encrypt the final
archive.    The   following   gadgets   will   then   become   active:
@{"Wipe noncrypted" LINK "ArcwipeGUI"}, @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"}, @{"New key" LINK "NewKeyGUI"}, @{"Remove" LINK "RemKey"} and @{"Sort" LINK "SortKeyGUI"}.

If this box is checked, and the @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"} is not empty, one or
more @{"ENCRYPT" LINK "ENCRYPT"} options will be put in the @{"commandfile" LINK "Commandfile"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ArcwipeGUI" "Wipe noncrypted"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
When  this  item  is  checked, the encrypted archive will be deleted -
this   is   the  default  behaviour.   Deselecting  this  item  equals
specifying the @{"ARCLIVE" LINK "ARCLIVE"} option in the @{"commandfile" LINK "Commandfile"}.

This  gadget  will  be  ghosted unless the @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"} checkbox is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "EncryptListGUI" "Recipient list"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
The  listview  within  the  Encryption  box,  contains a list over the
people  who  may  decrypt  the final archive.  The keys are shown with
their hex ID first, and the name of the person is listed to the right.
You  may use the arrows and scrollbar to the right to move up and down
in  the  list  view,  select  items by clicking on them, and use these
gadgets to manipulate it:
@{"New key" LINK "NewKeyGUI"}, @{"Remove" LINK "RemKey"} and @{"Sort" LINK "SortKeyGUI"}.

Double-clicking on an item will show more info about that key, if @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}
is properly installed (PGPPATH, etc.).

This  gadget  will  be  ghosted unless the @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"} checkbox is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NewKeyGUI" "New key"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
By clicking this gadget, a list of keys will pop up, where you may
select the keys of new people who may decrypt the archive. For docs
about how to use this window, click @{"here" LINK "PGPSelectWin"}.

This  gadget  will  be  ghosted unless the @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"} checkbox is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "RemKey" "Remove"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
By  clicking this gadget, the currently selected key (if any), will be
removed  from the @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"} gadget, and that person will thus NOT
be able to decrypt the archive.

This  gadget  will  be  ghosted unless the @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"} checkbox is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SortKeyGUI" "Sort"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
When  you click this gadget, the contents of the @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"} gadget
will be sorted alphabetically, making it easier to read.

This  gadget  will  be  ghosted unless the @{"Encrypt archive" LINK "EncryptarchiveGUI"} checkbox is
checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PrefsPart" "Prefs Part"
@TOC "UsageGUI"
The prefs part has the following parts:

    @{"Checksum .info" LINK "SuminfoGUI"}      - Message digest icon files?
    @{"Use ASCII armor" LINK "AddArmorGUI"}     - Make final archive suitable for e-mail?
    @{"ASCII deep check" LINK "DeepChkGUI"}    - Make ASCII test check the whole file?
    @{"Add PGP public key" LINK "AddPGPKey"}  - Include your pubkey in the @{"Checksumfile" LINK "SumfileGUI"}
    @{"Add script commands" LINK "AddscriptGUI"} - Add script, which checks signatures?
    @{"Only wait at end" LINK "EndwaitGUI"}    - Don't issue the Wait command between each cmd?
    @{"Wait command" LINK "WaitComGUI"}        - Command issued between @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} & MD5SUM in script.
    @{"Signature ID" LINK "SignatureGUI"}        - The user name to sign the checksum file with.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SuminfoGUI" "Checksum .info"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
By  default,  icons  are  not  summed, as only changing their position
before  redistributing is enough to make the check fail.  If you check
this box, they will be summed too, as the @{"SUMICON" LINK "SUMICON"} option will be added
to the commandfile.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AddArmorGUI" "Use ASCII armor"
@TOC "PrefsPart"

When  this  option is checked, the final archive output will end up as
7-bit  ASCII, suitable for posting via e-mail.  Currently, only @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} is
supported   as  encoder  (yes,  you  may  ASCII-fy  with  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}  without
necessarily encrypting), UU-encoding is currently not supported.

This   is   equivalent  to  specifying  the  @{"ADDARMOR" LINK "ADDARMOR"}  option  in  the
@{"CommandFile" LINK "CommandFile"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "DeepChkGUI" "ASCII deep check"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
Checking this box, is the same as specifying the @{"DEEPCHK" LINK "DEEPCHK"} option.  This
will  make the ASCII check run through the entire file (still aborting
at  first  `binary'  value), to determine whether the file is ASCII or
not.   In  some  cases  this may be preferable, the default is to only
check the first kilobyte.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AddPGPKey" "Add PGP public key"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
When  this  option  is turned on, your @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} public key will be added to
the  final  @{"checksum file" LINK "SumfileGUI"}.   This  is  the  default behaviour, but the
addition  of  the  key  may be unnecessary for internal distributions,
especially  if  you  have a lot of signatures, making the key big.  In
other cases, leave it on, cause if the recipient haven't got your key,
he/she can't check neither the signature nor the @{"message digests" LINK "Notes" 18}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "AddscriptGUI" "Add script commands"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
If  this box is checked, a script will be put in front of the checksum
file.   To  make  the  script work properly, a `-----BEGIN' executable
with  your  distribution (which btw.  is included with this one).  The
script added can be controlled somewhat with these gadgets:
@{"Only wait at end" LINK "EndwaitGUI"} and @{"Wait command" LINK "WaitComGUI"}.

By  default, only  the signatures are put in the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"} file, plus a
quick  description  of  how to check the files.  In some cases you may
wish  to  make  this  process  automatic.   To  make  the  script work
properly,  a  `-----BEGIN'  executable  is included automagically with
your  distribution  (which  btw.   is  included  with this one).

@{b}NOTE:   THIS  IS  A  SECURITY  HOLE.   THE  '-----BEGIN'  FILE  MAY BE
INFECTED,  OR REPLACED.  COMMANDS INFECTING THE SYSTEM MAY BE ADDED IN
FRONT  OF  THE PGP SIGNED PART.  IT IS INDEED DISCOURAGED THAT YOU USE
THIS OPTION.@{ub}

To  make  sure  you  are aware of this problem, you will be asked each
time  for  confirmation.   To  avoid  this,  add  this  line  to  your
S:User-Startup file:

    SetEnv "SignArchOpts" "do_not_ask_for_confirmation_of_autochk"

The -----BEGIN file is added because doing so will:
    1) avoid  AmigaDOS  message  like 'Can't find command '-----BEGIN'
(the ENTIRE file is interpreted as a normal AmigaDOS script!)
    2) check       that       the       @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}       begins      with
'-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----'   and  TWO  linefeeds.   This  is
necessary  to  avoid a bug in @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.  Both the script and the executable
should work with all kickstarts.

As  the  file  has  to  be  recreated for each run and is differs from
archive to archive, the only equality is that there is one code chunk
of 300 bytes (which is equal from file to file), and then a data chunk
which contains the name of the @{"SUMFILE" LINK "SUMFILE"}'s name.

This is btw. the same as specifying the @{"AUTOCHK" LINK "AUTOCHK"} option.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "EndwaitGUI" "Only wait at end"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
When  this box is checked, the script will only issue the @{"Wait command" LINK "WaitComGUI"}
at the end of the script, when the @{"Add script commands" LINK "AddscriptGUI"} box is checked.

Checking this box equals specifying the @{"ENDWAIT" LINK "ENDWAIT"} option.

This  gadget will be ghosted unless the @{"Add script commands" LINK "AddscriptGUI"} @{"prefs" LINK "PrefsPart"} item
is checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WaitComGUI" "Wait command"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
In  this  string  gadget, enter the command issued between each of the
cryptographic    commands,    or    only    at    the   end   if   the
@{"Only wait at end" LINK "EndwaitGUI"} Prefs item is checked.  Preferably, it will wait some
seconds, ask for user input or whatever, so that the user may read the
output from @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} and MD5SUM.

Ideas for wait commands:

Ask "Press <return> to continue..."    ; will wait until the user
                                       ; presses return

Wait 5                                 ; waits 5 seconds

etc.

Home-made waiting commands should be avoided, as they can be infected,
and may infect @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}, which will set off a tragic chain of events.

This  gadget will be ghosted unless the @{"Add script commands" LINK "AddscriptGUI"} @{"prefs" LINK "PrefsPart"} item
is checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SignatureGUI" "Signature ID"
@TOC "PrefsPart"
Enter  your  name  within @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} in this string gadget, the key this name
corresponds to will be used for signing the @{"checksumfile" LINK "SumfileGUI"}.  By clicking
the gadget to the right of the gadget, you may select the key with the
@{"PGP key-select requester" LINK "PGPSelectWin"}.

Please  note  if  you  leave  this  gadget  uninitialized,  the MyName
parameter  found  in  pgp.config  in  your  PGPPATH  dir  (if properly
initialized,  that  is) will be used as your name when talking to @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"}.
If  this  can't be found, the first key on your secret keyring will be
used.

The key ID returned from this requester is the hexadecimal ID number,
not  your name.  This is done to avoid confusion (if you for instance,
have more than one secret key).
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Menuoverview" "Overview of menu items"
@TOC "UsageGUI"
The following menu items are available:

Project
 @{"Open..." LINK "ProjOpen"}         - Open previously created commandfile
 @{"Save..." LINK "ProjSave"}         - Save settings to commandfile
 @{"Save as..." LINK "ProjSaveAs"}      - The same, but requesting file first
 @{"Global settings" LINK "ProjGlobSett"} - Set paths for needed programs
 @{"Create archive" LINK "ProjExec"}  - Create the archive (and crypt it?)!
 @{"About" LINK "ProjAbout"}           - Shows some info...
 @{"Quit" LINK "ProjQuit"}            - Only included for testing purposes...:)

Settings
 Prefs
  @{"Load..." LINK "SettPrefsLoad"}     - Loads the prefs settings ONLY
  @{"Save..." LINK "SettPrefsSave"}     - Saves the prefs settings ONLY
  @{"Clear..." LINK "SettPrefsClear"}    - Clears all prefs settings
 Encryption
  @{"Load..." LINK "SettEncrLoad"}     - Loads the names of keys ONLY
  @{"Merge..." LINK "SettEncrMerge"}    - Merge a namelist into the current
  @{"Save..." LINK "SettEncrSave"}     - Saves the names of keys ONLY
  @{"Clear..." LINK "SettEncrClear"}    - Clears all encryption settings
 Files
  @{"Load..." LINK "SettFilesLoad"}     - Loads filenames into the filelist ONLY
  @{"Merge..." LINK "SettFilesMerge"}    - Merge a filelist into the current
  @{"Save..." LINK "SettFilesSave"}     - Saves filenames in the filelist ONLY
  @{"Clear..." LINK "SettFilesClear"}    - Clears filelist and/or rootdir, etc.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjOpen" "Project->Open..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
Selecting this menu item will open a previously created @{"commandfile" LINK "Commandfile"}.
The options will be parsed, and the gadgets will be initialized
accordingly. The following options are ignored:

@{"ASCCHAR" LINK "ASCCHAR"}     - strips off eventual leading ASCCHAR's in filenames
@{"BINCHAR" LINK "BINCHAR"}     - strips off eventual leading BINCHAR's in filenames
@{"ADDCOMM" LINK "ADDCOMM"}     - ignored completely
@{"BANNERS" LINK "BANNERS"}     - ignored completely

You   may   also  only  load  parts  of  the  files,  for  this,  see:
@{"Settings->Prefs->Load..." LINK "SettPrefsLoad"}    to   load   the   prefs   settings   ONLY,
@{"Settings->Encryption->Load..." LINK "SettEncrLoad"}    to   load   the   pubkeys   ONLY  and
@{"Settings->Files->Load..." LINK "SettFilesLoad"}  to load the files in the filelist ONLY.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjSave" "Project->Save..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
Selecting  this  menu  item will save the settings of the gadgets into
the  previously selected option file.  If no option file is previously
selected,  the  program  will  request one with a filerequester, as in
Project->Save as...

If  you  wish  to  only  save  a  part  of  the  gadget settings, see:
@{"Settings->Prefs->Save..." LINK "SettPrefsSave"}      to     save    the    prefs    settings,
@{"Settings->Encryption->Save..." LINK "SettEncrSave"}      to    save    the    pubkeys    and
@{"Settings->Files->Save..." LINK "SettFilesSave"}  to save the files in the filelist.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjSaveAs" "Project->Save as..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
Selecting  this  menu  item will save the settings of the gadgets into
the  option  file entered in the file requester.  If no option file is
selected, nothing will happen.

If you wish to only save a particular part of the gadget settings, see
@{"Settings->Prefs->Save..." LINK "SettPrefsSave"}      to     save    the    prefs    settings,
@{"Settings->Encryption->Save..." LINK "SettEncrSave"}      to    save    the    pubkeys    and
@{"Settings->Files->Save..." LINK "SettFilesSave"}  to save the files in the filelist.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjGlobSett" "Project->Global Settings"
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menupoint will make a window pop up, where you may configure the
paths  for  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"},  RX  and the REXX script.  You should not do anything
else  than  specifying  the  program name, WITH PATH.  For @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} you may
also specify options, assuming you have @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} in "C:" :

C:PGP +PKCS_COMPAT=0

Just remember to NOT add any commands to the line, like "-kvv", etc.

Quick explanation of the string gadgets should contain:

PGP
        - The  name of your @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} binary program file, NOT the directory
          you've set up as PGPPATH.

RX 
        - The  command used for starting REXX programs.  Usually found
          in the Sys:Rexxc/ directory.

REXX
        - Full path & name for the SignArch.rexx script.

AmigaGuide
        - The  path  (with  filename)  for this document.  If it isn't
          installed,  set the filename to ":::N/A:::", and the program
          won't search for it.
LhA
        - Full path & name (plus possible options) for LhA

MD5Sum
        - The path & name for MD5SUM, the tool which was enclosed with
          PGP, and which will be used for creating signatures.


The other gadgets will do the following:

Auto-include icons?
        - When  checked,  this gadget will cause that when pushing the
          @{"Add files" LINK "AddfilesGUI"}  button,  automagically  include  associated .info
          files for the files you select.

Generate sumfile icon?
        - Will generate an icon for the sumfile, if it doesn't exist.

Save    - Save the settings for future use
Use     - Use the settings only this session (until reboot)
Cancel  - Do not use settings at all

Please note that all these parameters are initialized by the Installer
script.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjExec" "Project->Create archive"
@TOC "Menuoverview"
By  selecting  this  menupoint, signing and archiving will start!  The
settings will be saved to a temporary file, and the REXX script, which
does the job, will be invoked.  The input/output from this script will
appear in the console window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjAbout" "Project->About"
@TOC "Menuoverview"
Shows  some  info  about  me  and  the program.  Please remember these
@{"addresses" LINK "Address"} when  it's  Christmas,  in  case some unwanted A4000/040's,
Indy's, HD's, etc.  should show up...:)

Nah,  but  I  WOULD   L O V E   a postcard, anyway - at anytime of the
year!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ProjQuit" "Project->Quit"
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menuitem  was  included  for testing purposes, and will probably
have no practical use.  :)

Anyway,  it  will check whether you've changed the settings since last
save, and give you the choice of saving them first.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettPrefsLoad" "Settings->Prefs->Load..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menupoint  will  load  the  prefs  settings  from disk, ignoring
eventual  crypt and file information.  Thus, the only gadgets affected
by  this  operation,  will be those within the @{"Prefs box" LINK "PrefsPart"}.  Please note
that  these  files  begin  with `!!PREFS!!' instead of `!!FILELIST!!',
however, you may choose to ignore this when loading the datas.

Thus,  you  may  load only the prefs settings from another, previously
created, @{"commandfile" LINK "Commandfile"}.

These files are normally saved with @{"Settings->Prefs->Save..." LINK "SettPrefsSave"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettPrefsSave" "Settings->Prefs->Save..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menupoint  will save the prefs settings from disk, not including
crypt  and  file information.  Thus, the only gadget settings saved by
this  operation, will be those within the @{"Prefs box" LINK "PrefsPart"}.  Please note that
these files begin with `!!PREFS!!' instead of `!!FILELIST!!', however,
you   may   choose   to  ignore  this  when  loading  the  datas  with
@{"Project->Open..." LINK "ProjOpen"}

These files are normally loaded with @{"Settings->Prefs->Load..." LINK "SettPrefsLoad"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettPrefsClear" "Settings->Prefs->Clear..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
By selecting this menupoint, everything in the prefs rectangle will be
reset to default, and string requesters will be cleared.  Confirmation
will be asked for. Please note that the @{"Wipe noncrypted" LINK "ArcWipeGUI"} gadget also
will be affected by this.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettEncrLoad" "Settings->Encryption->Load..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This menupoint will load the files contained in the file selected into
the  @{"Recipient  list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"},  ignoring  eventual  prefs and file information.
Please  note  that  these  files  begin  with  `!!CRYPT!!'  instead of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas.

NOTE:   This  will  replace the contents of the @{"Recipient  list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"} gadget.
If  you  wish  to  simply  add to the contents of the gadgets, use the
@{"Settings->Encryption->Merge..." LINK "SettEncrMerge"} menupoint instead.

These files are normally saved with @{"Settings->Encryption->Save..." LINK "SettEncrSave"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettEncrMerge" "Settings->Encryption->Merge..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This menupoint will load the files contained in the file selected into
the  @{"Recipient  list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"},  ignoring  eventual  prefs and file information.
Please  note  that  these  files  begin  with  `!!CRYPT!!'  instead of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas.

NOTE:   In  contrast to @{"Settings->Encryption->Load..." LINK "SettEncrLoad"} menupoint, this one
is  non-destructive.   If  you  wish  to  replace  the contents of the
recipient list gadget, use that one instead.

These files are normally saved with @{"Settings->Encryption->Save..." LINK "SettEncrSave"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettEncrSave" "Settings->Encryption->Save..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menupoint  will  save the  files in the @{"Recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"} gadget to the
selected  file,  not  including  eventual files and prefs information.
Please  note  that  these  files  begin  with  `!!CRYPT!!'  instead of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas with @{"Project->Open..." LINK "ProjOpen"}

These files are normally loaded with @{"Settings->Encryption->Load..." LINK "SettEncrLoad"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettEncrClear" "Settings->Encryption->Clear..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This menupoint will, after the selection has been confirmed, flush all
recipients  from  the recipient list, and turn off encryption of final
archive.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettFilesLoad" "Settings->Files->Load..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This menupoint will load the files contained in the file selected into
the  @{"Filelist" LINK "FilelistGUI"},  ignoring eventual crypt and prefs information.  Please
note   that   these   files   begin   with   `!!FILES!!'   instead  of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas.

Thus, you may load files you normally sent to LhA with this menupoint.

NOTE:   This will replace the contents of the @{"FileList" LINK "FileListGUI"} gadget.  If you
wish   to  simply  add  to  the  contents  of  the  gadgets,  use  the
@{"Settings->Files->Merge..." LINK "SettFilesMerge"} menupoint instead.

These files are normally saved with @{"Settings->Files->Save..." LINK "SettFilesSave"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettFilesMerge" "Settings->Files->Merge..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This menupoint will load the files contained in the file selected into
the  @{"Filelist" LINK "FilelistGUI"},  ignoring eventual crypt and prefs information.  Please
note   that   these   files   begin   with   `!!FILES!!'   instead  of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas.

Thus, you may load files you normally sent to LhA with this menupoint.

NOTE:   In  contrast  to  @{"Settings->Files->Load" LINK "SettFilesLoad"} menupoint, this one is
non-destructive.   If you wish to replace the contents of the @{"FileList" LINK "FileListGUI"}
gadget, use that one instead.

These files are normally saved with @{"Settings->Files->Save..." LINK "SettFilesSave"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettFilesSave" "Settings->Files->Save..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
This  menupoint  will  save the  files in the @{"Filelist" LINK "FilelistGUI"} gadget to the
selected  file,  not  including  eventual crypt and prefs information.
Please  note  that  these  files  begin  with  `!!FILES!!'  instead of
`!!FILELIST!!',  however,  you  may choose to ignore this when loading
the datas with @{"Project->Open..." LINK "ProjOpen"}

These files are normally loaded with @{"Settings->Files->Load..." LINK "SettFilesLoad"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SettFilesClear" "Settings->Files->Clear..."
@TOC "Menuoverview"
When  you  wish  to  reset  the  filelist  and/or  the  @{"Checksum-file" LINK "SUMFILEGUI"},
@{"Root directory" LINK "RootdirGUI"},  @{"Archive" LINK "ArchiveGUI"}  or  @{"Include textfile" LINK "IncTextGUI"}, select this menupoint.
Beware  that  clearing  the  rootdir without clearing the filelist may
cause  all  filenames  to expand to full path - making it difficult to
get an overview.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGPSelectWin" "PGP key-select window"
@TOC "EncryptControl"
There are four gadgets, by clicking them, the following happens:

    @{"Use key" LINK "PGPSelUsekey"}         - Return the currently selected key
    @{"Search" LINK "PGPSelSearch"}          - This will search for a specified string.
    @{"Search next" LINK "PGPSelSNext"}     - Searches for the next occurence
    @{"Update" LINK "PGPSelUpd"}          - Re-reads the keyring from disk

If  you change your mind, and don't wish to select a key anyway, click
the close button in the upper left part of the window.

PLEASE  NOTE:   Sometimes,  nothing  is  displayed,  although  @{"PGP" LINK "PGP"} is
properly  installed  and  configured  in   @{"Global Settings" LINK "ProjGlobSett"}.   This  is
probably  because  you're  running  low  on memory - try free some and
click the @{"Update" LINK "PGPSelUpd"}  button.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGPSelUsekey" "Use key"
@TOC "PGPSelectWin"
Click  this  button,  and  the key selected will be returned.  If this
window was invoked by pressing @{"New key" LINK "NewKeyGUI"}, the key selected will be added
to the @{"recipient list" LINK "EncryptListGUI"}, with the hex ID first and then the name.  If it
was  started  by clicking the box beside @{"Signature ID" LINK "SignatureGUI"}, only the hex ID
will be returned, to avoid later confusion.

If  you  have  problems with locating a specific key (although they're
sorted  alphabetically  by  name,  not  hex  ID),  try  the @{"Search" LINK "PGPSelSearch"} and
@{"Search next" LINK "PGPSelSNext"} buttons.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGPSelSearch" "Search"
@TOC "PGPSelectWin"
When you click this button, a requester will pop up, asking for string
to   search   for.    The   program   will   then   search  downwards,
case-insensitive,  for  any  match  within  a  key's  hex  ID or name,
starting  at  the currently selected item, or at the top if nothing is
selected.  If nothing is found, you will be informed.

To continue searching for the same string, press @{"Search next" LINK "PGPSelSNext"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGPSelSNext" "Search next"
@TOC "PGPSelectWin"
Does  the  same  as @{"Search" LINK "PGPSelSearch"}, except that it won't re-ask for the search
string, unless the search string is empty. For more info on the search
procedure, look at the docs for @{"Search" LINK "PGPSelSearch"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGPSelUpd" "Update"
@TOC "PGPSelectWin"
Sometimes the keyring is changed while the program is running, a key
may be added. Thus, the list of keys in the @{"PGP key-select window" LINK "PGPSelectWin"} may
be incorrect. In such case, click this button to re-read the keyring
from the disk.

This will also correct problems when you're running low on memory - if
there's no mem available, nothing can be displayed.  If you have freed
some memory, click this gadget to retry loading.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PGP" "PGP"
Pretty  Good(tm) Privacy (PGP), from Phil's Pretty Good Software, is a
high  security  cryptographic  software  application  for MSDOS, Unix,
VAX/VMS,  and other computers.  PGP allows people to exchange files or
messages with privacy, authentication, and convenience.  Privacy means
that   only   those  intended  to  receive  a  message  can  read  it.
Authentication means that messages that appear to be from a particular
person  can  only have originated from that person.  Convenience means
that  privacy  and  authentication are provided without the hassles of
managing keys associated with conventional cryptographic software.  No
secure channels are needed to exchange keys between users, which makes
PGP  much  easier  to use.  This is because PGP is based on a powerful
new technology called "public key" cryptography.

PGP combines the convenience of the Rivest-Shamir-Adleman (RSA) public
key  cryptosystem with the speed of conventional cryptography, message
digests  for  digital  signatures, data compression before encryption,
good  ergonomic  design,  and  sophisticated  key management.  And PGP
performs  the  public-key  functions  faster  than most other software
implementations.  PGP is public key cryptography for the masses.

(Taken from "Volume I: Essential Topics" of the PGP documentation).
@ENDNODE

